The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Sunday, August 22, 2004 				 Cerebral attack alarm
 A STAFF REPORTER 																								Calcutta, Aug. 21: Alarmed at the sharp rise in the number of deaths due to cerebral attacks in urban areas, eminent neurologists and medical experts are gathering for a workshop tomorrow to formulate an effective strategy to fight the disease. 																								We will take part in a workshop to find out a more effective way to contain the ailment which leads to paralysis and immobility. We will prepare some guidelines and send them to the government for an action plan..., said Dipesh Mondal, a stroke specialist of Calcutta Medical College. 																								According to a rough estimate, every year at least 20,000 patients fall victim to cerebral attacks in the city alone. Of them, about 4,500 die and another 5,500 become fully paralysed. About 5,000 are paralysed partially. 																								The major causes are hypertension, smoking, stress and stress-related anxiety and tension, fast food habits, high ambition, lack of exercise and high blood sugar. 
